00:36:26,059 --> 00:36:29,228
Tax-free. The IRS can't touch one cent.

510
00:36:29,313 --> 00:36:31,898
You're the smart banker what killed his wife.

511
00:36:31,982 --> 00:36:35,526
Why should I believe a smart banker like you?
So I can end up in here with you?

512
00:36:35,611 --> 00:36:37,111
It's legal. Ask the IRS.

513
00:36:37,196 --> 00:36:40,406
They'll say the same thing.
But I feel stupid telling you this.

514
00:36:40,491 --> 00:36:42,784
I'm sure you would have investigated the matter.

515
00:36:42,868 --> 00:36:46,955
Yeah, I don't need no banker to tell me
where the bears shit in the buckwheat.

516
00:36:47,040 --> 00:36:50,083
Of course not, but you do need someone
to set up the tax-free gift.

517
00:36:50,168 --> 00:36:52,044
It'll cost you. A lawyer.

518
00:36:52,128 --> 00:36:54,463
A bunch of ball-washing bastards.

519
00:36:54,547 --> 00:36:58,383
I suppose I could set it up for you.
That would save you some money.

520
00:36:58,384 --> 00:37:00,761
If you get the forms, I'll prepare them for you.

521
00:37:00,845 --> 00:37:02,721
Nearly free of charge.

522
00:37:03,807 --> 00:37:07,184
I'd only ask three beers apiece
for each of my co-workers.

523
00:37:07,268 --> 00:37:09,686
Co-workers! Get him! That's rich, ain't it?

524
00:37:09,771 --> 00:37:13,232
I think a man working outdoors
feels more like a man

525
00:37:13,316 --> 00:37:15,067
if he can have a bottle of suds.

526
00:37:15,151 --> 00:37:18,195
That's only my opinion...sir.

527
00:37:21,616 --> 00:37:23,158
What are you jimmies staring at?

528
00:37:23,243 --> 00:37:24,243
Back to work!

529
00:37:24,327 --> 00:37:26,286
Let's go. Work.

530
00:37:34,671 --> 00:37:40,175
And that's how it came to pass...
that on the second-to-last day of the job,

531
00:37:40,260 --> 00:37:44,931
the convict crew that tarred the
plate-factory roof in the spring of '49...

532
00:37:45,015 --> 00:37:48,226
wound up sitting in a row
at ten o'clock in the morning,

533
00:37:48,310 --> 00:37:52,188
drinking icy-cold, Bohemia-style beer...

534
00:37:52,273 --> 00:37:57,485
courtesy of the hardest screw that ever
walked a turn at Shawshank State Prison.

535
00:37:57,570 --> 00:37:59,654
Drink up while it's cold, ladies.

536
00:38:01,031 --> 00:38:05,201
The colossal prick
even managed to sound magnanimous.

537
00:38:06,954 --> 00:38:11,583
We sat and drank with the sun on our shoulders,
and felt like free men.

538
00:38:11,667 --> 00:38:15,169
Hell, we could have been tarring the roof
of one of our own houses.

539
00:38:15,254 --> 00:38:18,548
We were the lords of all creation.

540
00:38:18,632 --> 00:38:23,177
As for Andy,
he spent that break hunkered in the shade...

541
00:38:23,262 --> 00:38:25,972
a strange little smile on his face,

542
00:38:26,056 --> 00:38:28,141
watching us drink his beer.

543
00:38:34,899 --> 00:38:36,441
Hey...

544
00:38:36,525 --> 00:38:37,817
Want a cold one, Andy?

545
00:38:37,902 --> 00:38:39,569
No, thanks.

546
00:38:39,653 --> 00:38:41,446
I gave up drinking.

547
00:38:45,285 --> 00:38:48,454
You could argue
he'd done it to curry favor with the guards.

548
00:38:48,538 --> 00:38:51,373
Or maybe make a few friends among us cons.

549
00:38:53,627 --> 00:38:57,087
Me, I think he did it just to feel normal again.

550
00:38:58,173 --> 00:39:00,257
If only for a short while.

551
00:39:03,136 --> 00:39:05,471
King me.

552
00:39:05,555 --> 00:39:07,973
Chess. Now, there's a game of kings.

553
00:39:08,058 --> 00:39:10,601
- What?
- Civilized, strategic.

554
00:39:10,685 --> 00:39:13,020
And a total fucking mystery.

555
00:39:13,104 --> 00:39:14,313
I hate it.

556
00:39:14,397 --> 00:39:16,315
Maybe you'll let me teach you someday.

557
00:39:16,399 --> 00:39:18,859
Yeah. Sure.

558
00:39:18,944 --> 00:39:21,070
I thought of getting a board together.

559
00:39:21,154 --> 00:39:23,948
Well, I'm the right man.
I'm the guy that can get things.

560
00:39:24,032 --> 00:39:25,532
We might do business on a board.

561
00:39:25,617 --> 00:39:28,410
But I want to carve the pieces myself.

562
00:39:28,495 --> 00:39:32,081
One side in alabaster, the opposing side
in soapstone. What do you think?

563
00:39:32,165 --> 00:39:34,083
I think it'll take years.

564
00:39:34,167 --> 00:39:36,752
Well, years I got.
What I don't have are the rocks.

565
00:39:36,836 --> 00:39:39,004
Pickings are pretty slim in the yard.

566
00:39:39,089 --> 00:39:41,049
Pebbles, mostly.

567
00:39:45,388 --> 00:39:48,264
Andy, we're getting to be kinda friends,
aren't we?

568
00:39:48,349 --> 00:39:50,016
Yeah, I guess.

569
00:39:51,143 --> 00:39:53,561
Can I ask you something?

570
00:39:53,646 --> 00:39:55,647
Why did you do it?

571
00:39:56,857 --> 00:40:00,735
I'm innocent, Red. Just
like everybody else here.

572
00:40:05,032 --> 00:40:07,117
What are you in for?

573
00:40:09,120 --> 00:40:10,120
Murder.

574
00:40:10,204 --> 00:40:11,621
Same as you.

575
00:40:11,706 --> 00:40:12,872
Innocent?

576
00:40:15,543 --> 00:40:17,627
Only guilty man in Shawshank.

577
00:41:17,105 --> 00:41:18,689
Where's the canary?

578
00:41:18,774 --> 00:41:20,107
How did you know?

579
00:41:20,108 --> 00:41:21,275
How did I know what?

580
00:41:21,359 --> 00:41:23,778
So, you don't know? Come.

581
00:41:26,531 --> 00:41:28,657
This is where the canary is, Johnny.

582
00:41:31,036 --> 00:41:35,039
Quite a surprise to hear a woman singing
in my house, eh, Johnny?

583
00:41:37,960 --> 00:41:40,337
That's quite a...

584
00:41:40,421 --> 00:41:42,089
surprise.

585
00:41:44,592 --> 00:41:46,301
Red...

586
00:41:46,385 --> 00:41:48,178
Wait, wait, wait, wait.

587
00:41:48,262 --> 00:41:50,097
Here she comes.

588
00:41:50,181 --> 00:41:53,058
This is the part I like -
when she does that shit with her hair.

589
00:41:53,142 --> 00:41:56,061
Yeah, I know. I've seen
it three times this month.

590
00:41:56,145 --> 00:41:58,146
Gilda, are you decent?

591
00:41:58,231 --> 00:42:00,273
Me?

592
00:42:01,984 --> 00:42:04,027
Hah! God, I love it!

593
00:42:09,909 --> 00:42:13,703
I understand
you're a man that knows how to get things.

594
00:42:13,788 --> 00:42:17,666
Yeah, I'm known to locate certain things
from time to time. What do you want?

595
00:42:17,750 --> 00:42:20,252
- Rita Hayworth.
- What?

596
00:42:20,336 --> 00:42:22,170
Can you get her?

597
00:42:23,256 --> 00:42:26,716
So, this is Johnny Farrell.
I've heard a lot about you, Johnny.

598
00:42:26,801 --> 00:42:28,677
Take a few weeks.

599
00:42:28,761 --> 00:42:29,970
Weeks?

600
00:42:29,971 --> 00:42:32,598
Well, yeah, Andy. I don't
have her stuffed down the

601
00:42:32,599 --> 00:42:35,226
front of my pants right now, I'm sorry to say.

602
00:42:35,310 --> 00:42:37,812
But I'll get her. Relax.

603
00:42:40,065 --> 00:42:41,566
Thanks.

604
00:42:41,650 --> 00:42:43,651
- It was a surprise, Mr. Farrell.
- It was.

605
00:42:43,735 --> 00:42:44,777
Sit down.

606
00:42:44,862 --> 00:42:46,779
Did you tell him what I'm doing here?

607
00:42:46,864 --> 00:42:49,699
No, I wanted to save that as a surprise, too.

608
00:42:49,783 --> 00:42:51,450
Hang on to your hat, Mr. Farrell...

609
00:43:01,545 --> 00:43:03,796
- Take a walk.
- I gotta change the reel.

610
00:43:03,881 --> 00:43:05,965
I said fuck off!

611
00:43:10,804 --> 00:43:13,598
Ain't you gonna scream?

612
00:43:14,975 --> 00:43:16,767
Let's get this over with.

613
00:43:20,898 --> 00:43:22,523
He broke my fuckin' nose!

614
00:43:33,036 --> 00:43:37,080
Now...I'm gonna open my fly...

615
00:43:37,165 --> 00:43:40,125
and you're gonna swallow
what I give you to swallow.

616
00:43:41,211 --> 00:43:43,003
Then you're gonna swallow Rooster's.

617
00:43:43,087 --> 00:43:45,923
You broke his nose,
he ought to have something to show for it.

618
00:43:46,007 --> 00:43:48,217
Anything you put in my mouth,
you're gonna lose.

619
00:43:48,301 --> 00:43:51,053
No. You don't understand.

620
00:43:51,137 --> 00:43:54,431
You do that, and I'll put
all eight inches of this steel in your ear.

621
00:43:54,432 --> 00:43:55,515
All right.

622
00:43:55,600 --> 00:44:00,229
But you should know that sudden, serious brain
injury causes the victim to bite down hard.

623
00:44:01,481 --> 00:44:03,899
In fact, I hear the bite reflex is so strong,

624
00:44:03,983 --> 00:44:08,779
they have to pry the victim's jaws open...
with a crowbar.

625
00:44:11,616 --> 00:44:13,242
Where did you get this shit?

626
00:44:13,326 --> 00:44:14,993
I read it.

627
00:44:16,079 --> 00:44:18,956
Know how to read, you ignorant fuck?

628
00:44:20,458 --> 00:44:22,334
Honey...

629
00:44:23,586 --> 00:44:25,963
..you shouldn't.

630
00:44:28,007 --> 00:44:31,010
Bogs didn't put anything in Andy's mouth...

631
00:44:31,095 --> 00:44:33,471
and neither did his friends.

632
00:44:33,555 --> 00:44:36,849
What they did do...
is beat him within an inch of his life.

633
00:44:38,060 --> 00:44:40,061
Andy spent a month in the infirmary.

634
00:44:41,105 --> 00:44:43,606
Bogs spent a week in the hole.

635
00:44:48,070 --> 00:44:49,696
Time's up, Bogs.

636
00:44:53,367 --> 00:44:55,451
It's your world, boss.

637
00:44:57,538 --> 00:45:00,957
Return to your cell blocks for evening count.

638
00:45:01,041 --> 00:45:03,209
All prisoners report for lockdown.

639
00:45:18,767 --> 00:45:20,059
What?

640
00:45:32,532 --> 00:45:35,242
Where's he going?
Grab his ankles.

641
00:45:36,828 --> 00:45:39,330
No! No!

642
00:45:39,414 --> 00:45:40,789
No!

643
00:45:40,874 --> 00:45:42,207
Help me...

644
00:45:42,292 --> 00:45:43,584
Aaarghh!

645
00:45:45,879 --> 00:45:48,547
Two things never happened again after that.

646
00:45:48,631 --> 00:45:51,467
The Sisters never laid a finger on Andy again...

647
00:45:52,677 --> 00:45:55,387
..and Bogs never walked again.

648
00:45:56,514 --> 00:45:59,933
They transferred him
to a minimum-security hospital upstate.

649
00:46:00,018 --> 00:46:05,731
To my knowledge, he lived out the rest
of his days drinking his food through a straw.

650
00:46:05,815 --> 00:46:10,486
I'm thinking Andy could use a nice welcome
back when he gets out of the infirmary.

651
00:46:11,613 --> 00:46:15,407
Sounds good to us.
I figure we owe him that much for the beer.

652
00:46:16,785 --> 00:46:19,453
The man likes to play chess.

653
00:46:19,537 --> 00:46:21,622
Let's get him some rocks.

654
00:46:54,031 --> 00:46:55,907
Guys...

655
00:46:55,991 --> 00:46:58,368
I got one. I got one. Look.

656
00:47:00,788 --> 00:47:02,872
Heywood, that isn't soapstone.

657
00:47:02,957 --> 00:47:05,166
And it ain't alabaster, either.

658
00:47:05,251 --> 00:47:06,876
What are you, a fucking geologist?

659
00:47:06,961 --> 00:47:09,003
He's right. It ain't.

660
00:47:09,088 --> 00:47:10,338
Well, what the hell is it?

661
00:47:10,423 --> 00:47:12,966
A horse apple.

662
00:47:13,050 --> 00:47:16,177
- Bullshit.
- No, horse shit. Petrified.

663
00:47:22,560 --> 00:47:25,438
Oh, Jesus Christ!

664
00:47:25,522 --> 00:47:27,481
Oh, damn!

665
00:47:27,566 --> 00:47:31,527
Despite a few hitches,
the boys came through in fine style.

666
00:47:32,737 --> 00:47:35,364
And by the weekend he was due back,
we had enough rocks

667
00:47:35,449 --> 00:47:38,492
to keep him busy till rapture.

668
00:47:38,577 --> 00:47:41,287
I also got a big shipment in that week.

669
00:47:41,371 --> 00:47:43,914
Cigarettes. Chewing gum.

670
00:47:43,999 --> 00:47:45,499
Sipping whisky.

671
00:47:45,584 --> 00:47:49,128
Playing cards with naked ladies on them.
You name it.

672
00:47:49,212 --> 00:47:52,173
And of course, the most important item.

673
00:47:53,925 --> 00:47:56,010
Rita Hayworth herself.

674
00:48:30,171 --> 00:48:33,006
OK, look alive! Open all tiers.

675
00:48:33,090 --> 00:48:35,425
Heads up. They're tossing the cells.

676
00:48:35,510 --> 00:48:37,761
Heads up. They're tossing the cells.

677
00:48:39,889 --> 00:48:41,765
119.

678
00:48:43,267 --> 00:48:44,935
123.

679
00:48:54,403 --> 00:48:56,279
On your feet.

680
00:48:57,990 --> 00:48:59,866
Face the wall.

681
00:49:34,361 --> 00:49:36,445
Turn around and face the Warden.

682
00:49:42,160 --> 00:49:44,245
Pleased to see you reading this.

683
00:49:45,622 --> 00:49:47,915
Any favorite passages?

684
00:49:48,959 --> 00:49:54,088
"Watch ye, therefore, for ye know not
when the master of the house cometh."

685
00:49:55,132 --> 00:49:58,009
Mark 13:35.

686
00:49:58,093 --> 00:50:00,761
I always liked that one.

687
00:50:00,846 --> 00:50:02,346
But I prefer...

688
00:50:02,431 --> 00:50:05,182
"I'm the light of the world.

689
00:50:05,267 --> 00:50:08,811
He that followeth me shall not walk in darkness,
but shall have the light of life."

690
00:50:08,895 --> 00:50:11,480
John, Chapter 8, Verse 12.

691
00:50:11,565 --> 00:50:15,026
I hear you're good with numbers. How nice.

692
00:50:16,153 --> 00:50:18,237
A man should have a skill.

693
00:50:20,325 --> 00:50:21,783
Wanna explain this?

694
00:50:22,869 --> 00:50:26,330
It's called a rock blanket.
It's for shaping and polishing rocks.

695
00:50:27,373 --> 00:50:29,333
A little hobby of mine.

696
00:50:40,178 --> 00:50:43,180
It's pretty clean. Some contraband here,

697
00:50:43,264 --> 00:50:45,349
but nothing to get in a twist over.

698
00:50:49,187 --> 00:50:51,271
I can't say I approve of this.

699
00:50:52,774 --> 00:50:54,483
But I suppose...

700
00:50:56,444 --> 00:50:58,320
..exceptions can be made.

701
00:51:08,706 --> 00:51:10,999
Lock 'em up!

702
00:51:13,002 --> 00:51:14,961
I almost forgot.

703
00:51:15,046 --> 00:51:17,298
I'd hate to deprive you of this.

704
00:51:17,383 --> 00:51:18,841
Salvation lies within.

705
00:51:19,927 --> 00:51:21,260
Yes, sir.

706
00:51:29,561 --> 00:51:32,146
Tossing cells was just an excuse.

707
00:51:32,690 --> 00:51:36,275
The truth is, Norton wanted to size Andy up.

708
00:51:49,915 --> 00:51:53,042
My wife made that in church group.

709
00:51:55,379 --> 00:51:56,713
Very nice, sir.

710
00:51:57,881 --> 00:51:59,757
Do you enjoy working in the laundry?

711
00:52:01,385 --> 00:52:03,094
No, sir, not especially.

712
00:52:03,178 --> 00:52:05,972
Perhaps we can find something more...

713
00:52:06,056 --> 00:52:08,141
befitting a man of your education.

714
00:52:16,484 --> 00:52:18,152
Hey, Jake. Where's Brooks?

715
00:52:18,236 --> 00:52:19,528
Andy.

716
00:52:19,612 --> 00:52:21,905
I thought I heard you out here!

717
00:52:23,408 --> 00:52:24,992
I've been reassigned to you.

718
00:52:25,076 --> 00:52:28,245
I know. They told me.

719
00:52:28,329 --> 00:52:30,414
Ain't that a kick in the head?

720
00:52:30,498 --> 00:52:33,000
Well, I'll give you the dime tour.

721
00:52:33,084 --> 00:52:35,169
Come on.

722
00:52:35,253 --> 00:52:37,421
Well, here she is.

723
00:52:37,505 --> 00:52:40,048
Shawshank Prison library.

724
00:52:40,133 --> 00:52:43,010
National Geographics.

725
00:52:43,094 --> 00:52:45,929
Reader's Digest condensed books.

726
00:52:46,014 --> 00:52:48,307
Louis L'Amour.

727
00:52:48,308 --> 00:52:50,434
Look Magazine.

728
00:52:50,518 --> 00:52:53,020
Erle Stanley Gardners.

729
00:52:53,104 --> 00:52:56,648
Every evening,
I load up the cart and make my round.

730
00:52:56,649 --> 00:52:59,818
I enter the names on this clipboard here.

731
00:52:59,903 --> 00:53:03,363
Easy-peasy, Japanesey. Any questions?

732
00:53:03,448 --> 00:53:06,408
Brooks, how long have you been librarian?

733
00:53:06,493 --> 00:53:11,663
Oh...I come here in '05,
and they made me librarian in 1912.

734
00:53:11,748 --> 00:53:15,126
And in all that time,
have you ever had an assistant?

735
00:53:15,211 --> 00:53:17,796
No. No, not much to it, really.

736
00:53:17,880 --> 00:53:19,798
Well, why me? Why now?

737
00:53:19,882 --> 00:53:21,382
I don't know,

738
00:53:21,467 --> 00:53:24,803
but it'll be nice to have some company
down here for a change.

739
00:53:24,804 --> 00:53:26,888
Dufresne!

740
00:53:36,190 --> 00:53:38,274
That's him. That's the one.

741
00:53:45,825 --> 00:53:47,116
I'm Dekins.

742
00:53:47,201 --> 00:53:49,661
I was er...

743
00:53:49,745 --> 00:53:53,748
thinking about maybe setting up
some kind of trust fund for my kids' educations.

744
00:53:56,085 --> 00:53:57,544
Oh...

745
00:53:57,628 --> 00:53:59,295
I see.

746
00:54:00,756 --> 00:54:02,632
Well, erm...

747
00:54:04,009 --> 00:54:05,552
..why don't we have a seat,

748
00:54:05,636 --> 00:54:07,720
and talk it over?

749
00:54:10,266 --> 00:54:13,185
Brooks,
do you have a piece of paper and a pencil?

750
00:54:24,656 --> 00:54:26,365
Thanks.

751
00:54:26,449 --> 00:54:28,117
So...

752
00:54:29,369 --> 00:54:31,871
Mr. Dekins...

753
00:54:31,955 --> 00:54:36,417
And then Andy says to Mr. Dekins,
"Do you want your sons to go to Harvard,

754
00:54:36,501 --> 00:54:38,627
- or Yale?"
- He didn't say that?

755
00:54:38,712 --> 00:54:41,380
As God is my witness, he did!

756
00:54:41,464 --> 00:54:44,842
Dekins just blinked for a second.
Then he laughed himself silly.

757
00:54:44,926 --> 00:54:46,802
And afterwards he shook Andy's hand.

758
00:54:46,887 --> 00:54:48,262
My ass!

759
00:54:48,346 --> 00:54:49,555
Shook his hand.

760
00:54:49,639 --> 00:54:52,600
Hell, I...I near soiled myself!

761
00:54:52,684 --> 00:54:56,896
All Andy needed was a suit and a tie
and a little jiggly hula girl on his desk,

762
00:54:56,980 --> 00:54:58,314
and he would have been:

763
00:54:58,398 --> 00:54:59,940
"Mr. Dufresne, if you please"!

764
00:55:00,025 --> 00:55:01,775
Making a few friends, Andy?

765
00:55:02,819 --> 00:55:04,778
I wouldn't say "friends".

766
00:55:04,863 --> 00:55:08,867
I'm a convicted murderer
who provides sound financial planning.

767
00:55:08,951 --> 00:55:11,286
It's a wonderful pet to have.

768
00:55:11,370 --> 00:55:13,288
Got you out of the laundry, though.

769
00:55:13,372 --> 00:55:15,582
Well, it might do more than that.

770
00:55:15,666 --> 00:55:18,668
How about expanding the library?
Get some new books in there.

771
00:55:18,753 --> 00:55:21,463
If you're gonna ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

772
00:55:21,547 --> 00:55:24,007
- Right.
- How do you expect to do that?

773
00:55:24,091 --> 00:55:29,346
I mean, get new books in here,
Mr. Dufresne, if you please?

774
00:55:29,430 --> 00:55:31,181
Ask the Warden for funds.

775
00:55:32,600 --> 00:55:35,894
Son, son. Six wardens
have been through here in my tenure,

776
00:55:35,978 --> 00:55:39,606
and I've learned one immutable, universal truth.

777
00:55:39,690 --> 00:55:41,399
Not one of them born...

778
00:55:41,400 --> 00:55:46,363
whose asshole wouldn't pucker up tighter than
a snare drum when you asked them for funds.

779
00:55:46,447 --> 00:55:48,740
The budget's stretched thin, as it is.

780
00:55:48,824 --> 00:55:50,075
I see.

781
00:55:50,159 --> 00:55:53,703
Perhaps I could write to the State Senate
and request funds from them.

782
00:55:53,788 --> 00:55:58,166
As far as they're concerned, there's only three
ways to spend money when it comes to prisons:

783
00:55:58,250 --> 00:56:00,335
more walls, more bars and more guards.

784
00:56:00,419 --> 00:56:04,839
Still, I'd like to try, with your permission.
A letter a week. They can't ignore me forever.

785
00:56:04,924 --> 00:56:06,466
Sure can.

786
00:56:06,550 --> 00:56:09,428
But you write your letters,
if it makes you happy.

787
00:56:09,513 --> 00:56:11,806
I'll even mail them for you. How's that?

788
00:56:13,725 --> 00:56:16,769
So, Andy started writing a letter a week,

789
00:56:16,853 --> 00:56:18,938
just like he said.

790
00:56:22,985 --> 00:56:27,113
And, just like Norton said, Andy got no answers.

791
00:56:34,955 --> 00:56:40,459
The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.

792
00:56:40,544 --> 00:56:43,629
The year after that, he did them all...

793
00:56:43,714 --> 00:56:45,798
including the Warden's.

794
00:56:47,175 --> 00:56:50,928
The year after that, they rescheduled
the start of the intramural season

795
00:56:51,013 --> 00:56:53,097
to coincide with tax season.

796
00:56:55,392 --> 00:56:59,603
The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.

797
00:56:59,688 --> 00:57:03,816
So, Moresby Prison issued you your gun,
but you had to pay for it?

798
00:57:03,900 --> 00:57:05,652
Damn right. The holster, too.

799
00:57:05,737 --> 00:57:06,987
That's tax-deductible.

800
00:57:07,071 --> 00:57:08,238
You can write that off.

801
00:57:08,322 --> 00:57:11,658
Yes, sir.
Andy was a regular cottage industry.

802
00:57:11,743 --> 00:57:14,786
In fact, it got so busy at tax time...

803
00:57:14,871 --> 00:57:16,913
he was allowed a staff.

804
00:57:16,998 --> 00:57:19,458
Hey, Red, can you hand me a stack of 1040s?

805
00:57:19,542 --> 00:57:22,210
It got me out of the wood shop
a month out of the year,

806
00:57:22,295 --> 00:57:24,963
and that was fine by me.

807
00:57:25,048 --> 00:57:28,425
And still...he kept sending those letters.

808
00:57:33,723 --> 00:57:35,557
Red, Andy.

809
00:57:35,641 --> 00:57:36,850
It's Brooks.

810
00:57:36,934 --> 00:57:39,394
Watch the door.

811
00:57:39,479 --> 00:57:41,063
Please, Brooks.

812
00:57:41,147 --> 00:57:43,148
- Just calm the fuck down.
- Stay back!

813
00:57:43,232 --> 00:57:45,275
- Stay back!
- What the hell's going on?

814
00:57:45,359 --> 00:57:48,445
You tell me. One second he's fine.
Then out comes the knife.

815
00:57:48,529 --> 00:57:50,989
Brooks, we can talk about this. Right?

816
00:57:51,074 --> 00:57:53,200
Nothing to talk about, goddamn it!

817
00:57:53,284 --> 00:57:54,993
I'm gonna cut his fucking throat.

818
00:57:55,078 --> 00:57:56,953
Heywood? Wait, what's he done to you?

819
00:57:57,038 --> 00:57:59,164
It's what they done!

820
00:57:59,248 --> 00:58:00,665
I...I got no choice...

821
00:58:00,750 --> 00:58:03,419
You're not gonna hurt him.
Even Heywood knows that.

822
00:58:03,504 --> 00:58:06,130
- Right, Heywood?
- I...I know that, sure.

823
00:58:06,215 --> 00:58:09,634
You won't hurt him, because he's a friend,
and you're a reasonable man.

824
00:58:09,718 --> 00:58:11,010
That's right. Right, guys?

825
00:58:11,095 --> 00:58:14,472
- Yes.
- So, put the knife down. Brooks, look at me.

826
00:58:14,556 --> 00:58:16,390
Put the knife down.

827
00:58:17,476 --> 00:58:18,643
Brooks...

828
00:58:18,727 --> 00:58:20,978
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

829
00:58:21,063 --> 00:58:23,397
Brooks, look at his neck. It's bleeding.

830
00:58:24,733 --> 00:58:26,317
It's the only...

831
00:58:26,401 --> 00:58:28,694
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

832
00:58:28,779 --> 00:58:31,364
Come on. This is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

833
00:58:31,365 --> 00:58:33,449
Put it down.

834
00:58:40,833 --> 00:58:45,545
Come on. Take it easy.
You're going to be all right.

835
00:58:45,629 --> 00:58:47,004
Him?

836
00:58:47,089 --> 00:58:50,758
Hell, what about me?
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat.

837
00:58:50,843 --> 00:58:53,469
Shit, Heywood,
you've had worse from shaving.

838
00:58:53,554 --> 00:58:55,805
What the hell did you do to set him off, anyway?

839
00:58:55,889 --> 00:58:58,224
Nothing. I come in here to say fare-thee-well.

840
00:58:58,308 --> 00:59:01,436
Ain't you heard? His parole's come through.

841
00:59:03,481 --> 00:59:06,608
I just don't understand what happened in there.
That's all.

842
00:59:06,693 --> 00:59:09,278
The old man's as crazy
as a rat in a tin shithouse.

843
00:59:09,362 --> 00:59:11,572
Oh, Heywood, that's enough out of you.

844
00:59:11,656 --> 00:59:14,658
- I heard he had you shitting in your pants.
- Fuck you!

845
00:59:14,742 --> 00:59:16,118
Would you knock it off?

846
00:59:16,202 --> 00:59:18,537
Brooks ain't no bug.

847
00:59:18,621 --> 00:59:20,497
He's just...

848
00:59:22,375 --> 00:59:24,209
He's just institutionalized.

849
00:59:25,545 --> 00:59:27,212
Institutionalized, my ass.

850
00:59:27,297 --> 00:59:31,592
The man's been in here 50 years, Heywood.
50 years.

851
00:59:31,676 --> 00:59:33,385
This is all he knows.

852
00:59:33,469 --> 00:59:35,888
In here, he's an important man.

853
00:59:35,972 --> 00:59:37,431
He's an educated man.

854
00:59:37,515 --> 00:59:39,600
Outside, he's nothing.

855
00:59:41,769 --> 00:59:44,396
Just a used-up con with arthritis in both hands.

856
00:59:44,480 --> 00:59:47,691
Probably couldn't get a
library card if he tried.

857
00:59:47,775 --> 00:59:49,860
You know what I'm trying to say?

858
00:59:49,944 --> 00:59:52,696
Red, I do believe you're
talking out of your ass.

859
00:59:53,948 --> 00:59:56,867
You believe whatever you want, Floyd.

860
00:59:56,868 --> 00:59:59,412
But I'm telling you, these walls are funny.

861
01:00:00,831 --> 01:00:02,916
First you hate 'em...

862
01:00:04,460 --> 01:00:06,544
..then you get used to 'em.

863
01:00:08,172 --> 01:00:10,798
Enough time passes...

864
01:00:10,883 --> 01:00:13,843
you get so you depend on 'em.

865
01:00:13,928 --> 01:00:16,262
That's institutionalized.

866
01:00:16,347 --> 01:00:17,722
Shit.

867
01:00:17,723 --> 01:00:19,349
You can never get like that.

868
01:00:19,433 --> 01:00:21,351
Oh, yeah?

869
01:00:21,435 --> 01:00:24,020
Say that when you've been here
as long as Brooks has.

870
01:00:24,104 --> 01:00:25,980
Goddamn right.

871
01:00:28,317 --> 01:00:30,860
They send you here for life.

872
01:00:30,945 --> 01:00:33,029
That's exactly what they take.

873
01:00:34,949 --> 01:00:37,033
The part that counts, anyway.

874
01:00:44,541 --> 01:00:46,709
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

875
01:00:48,629 --> 01:00:50,463
You go on, now.

876
01:00:51,548 --> 01:00:56,219
You're free.

877
01:01:12,112 --> 01:01:13,988
Bye.

878
01:01:15,073 --> 01:01:16,991
Good luck, Brooks.

879
01:01:53,570 --> 01:01:56,281
Dear fellas...

880
01:01:56,365 --> 01:02:00,577
I can't believe
how fast things move on the outside.

881
01:02:01,996 --> 01:02:05,040
Watch it, old-timer! Are
you trying to get killed?

882
01:02:05,124 --> 01:02:08,460
I saw an automobile once, when I was a kid,

883
01:02:08,544 --> 01:02:11,463
but now...they're everywhere.

884
01:02:15,676 --> 01:02:19,262
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

885
01:02:35,613 --> 01:02:41,910
The parole board got me into
this halfway house called The Brewer,

886
01:02:41,994 --> 01:02:45,789
and a job bagging groceries at the Foodway.

887
01:02:47,833 --> 01:02:53,171
It's hard work, and I try to keep up,
but my hands hurt most of the time.

888
01:02:53,256 --> 01:02:55,257
Make sure your man double-bags.

889
01:02:55,342 --> 01:02:57,593
Last time, the bottom near came out.

890
01:02:57,677 --> 01:03:00,971
Make sure you double-bag, like the lady says.
Understand?

891
01:03:01,056 --> 01:03:02,515
Yes, sir. I surely will.

892
01:03:02,599 --> 01:03:06,394
I don't think
the store manager likes me very much.

893
01:03:09,356 --> 01:03:14,151
Sometimes, after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

894
01:03:14,236 --> 01:03:19,573
I keep thinking Jake might just show up
and say hello.

895
01:03:19,658 --> 01:03:21,450
But he never does.

896
01:03:22,536 --> 01:03:27,915
And I hope, wherever he is,
he's doing OK and making new friends.

897
01:03:31,420 --> 01:03:34,338
I have trouble sleeping at night.

898
01:03:34,423 --> 01:03:37,216
I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.

899
01:03:38,301 --> 01:03:40,219
I wake up, scared.

900
01:03:40,303 --> 01:03:44,306
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

901
01:03:45,934 --> 01:03:47,393
Maybe I should get me a gun

902
01:03:47,477 --> 01:03:51,356
and rob the Foodway, so they'd send me home.

903
01:03:51,441 --> 01:03:53,775
I could shoot the manager, while I was at it.

904
01:03:53,860 --> 01:03:55,819
Sort of like a bonus.

905
01:03:57,321 --> 01:04:01,575
I guess I'm too old for that sort of nonsense
any more.

906
01:04:01,659 --> 01:04:03,702
I don't like it here.

907
01:04:03,786 --> 01:04:06,455
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.

908
01:04:06,539 --> 01:04:07,622
I've decided...

909
01:04:07,707 --> 01:04:09,583
not to stay.

910
01:04:20,928 --> 01:04:24,431
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.

911
01:04:24,515 --> 01:04:26,600
Not for an old crook like me.

912
01:05:29,623 --> 01:05:33,668
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.
Not for an old crook like me.

913
01:05:34,836 --> 01:05:38,881
PS. Tell Heywood
I'm sorry I put a knife to his throat.

914
01:05:38,882 --> 01:05:40,967
No hard feelings. Brooks."

915
01:05:51,688 --> 01:05:53,772
He should have died in here.

916
01:05:59,195 --> 01:06:03,657
What the fuck have you done?
It's a goddamn mess. I'll tell you that.

917
01:06:08,371 --> 01:06:09,788
What's all this?

918
01:06:09,872 --> 01:06:13,750
You tell me, fuck-stick.
They're all addressed to you.

919
01:06:13,835 --> 01:06:15,127
Take it.

920
01:06:24,095 --> 01:06:25,679
"Dear Mr. Dufresne...

921
01:06:26,764 --> 01:06:28,765
In response to your repeated enquiries,

922
01:06:28,850 --> 01:06:33,562
the State has allocated the enclosed funds
for your library project."

923
01:06:33,646 --> 01:06:35,022
This is 200 dollars.

924
01:06:36,065 --> 01:06:39,985
"In addition, the Library District
has generously responded

925
01:06:40,069 --> 01:06:42,779
with a charitable donation
of used books and sundries.

926
01:06:42,864 --> 01:06:44,948
We trust this will fill your needs.

927
01:06:45,033 --> 01:06:49,162
We now consider the matter closed.
Please stop sending us letters."

928
01:06:49,246 --> 01:06:52,081
I want all this cleared out
before the Warden gets back.

929
01:06:52,166 --> 01:06:53,833
Yes, sir.

930
01:06:57,588 --> 01:06:58,963
Good for you, Andy.

931
01:07:01,592 --> 01:07:03,051
Wow!

932
01:07:04,136 --> 01:07:06,220
It only took six years.

933
01:07:07,514 --> 01:07:10,391
From now on,
I'll write two letters a week, instead of one.

934
01:07:10,476 --> 01:07:14,020
Oh, I believe you're crazy enough.
You'd better get all this stuff out,

935
01:07:14,104 --> 01:07:15,271
like the Captain said.

936
01:07:15,356 --> 01:07:19,233
Now, I'm gonna go pinch a loaf.
When I come back, this is all gone, right?

937
01:07:25,407 --> 01:07:27,408
Wow.

938
01:07:57,482 --> 01:08:00,192
Duettino from The Marriage Of Figaro

939
01:08:01,653 --> 01:08:04,238
# Sull'aria...

940
01:08:07,867 --> 01:08:08,867
Andy,

941
01:08:08,952 --> 01:08:10,285
do you hear that?

942
01:08:10,370 --> 01:08:14,081
#..zeffiretto

943
01:08:26,302 --> 01:08:34,143
# Questa será spirera

944
01:09:04,550 --> 01:09:08,845
# Sotto i pini

945
01:09:08,929 --> 01:09:14,142
# Del boschetto

946
01:09:15,644 --> 01:09:18,021
# Sotto i pini...

947
01:09:18,105 --> 01:09:20,982
Dufresne?

948
01:09:21,066 --> 01:09:22,650
Dufresne?

949
01:09:22,735 --> 01:09:24,819
Andy, let me out.

950
01:09:27,531 --> 01:09:31,075
Andy?

951
01:09:31,160 --> 01:09:36,331
I have no idea to this day what those
two Italian ladies were singing about.

952
01:09:36,415 --> 01:09:38,833
The truth is, I don't want to know.

953
01:09:38,918 --> 01:09:41,003
Some things are best left unsaid.

954
01:09:45,050 --> 01:09:47,572
I like to think they were
singing about something

955
01:09:47,573 --> 01:09:50,095
so beautiful, it can't be expressed in words...

956
01:09:50,180 --> 01:09:52,556
and makes your heart ache because of it.

957
01:09:54,768 --> 01:09:57,478
I tell you, those voices soared...

958
01:09:57,562 --> 01:10:02,107
higher and farther
than anybody in a grey place dares to dream.

959
01:10:02,192 --> 01:10:05,569
It was like some beautiful bird
flapped into our drab little cage

960
01:10:05,654 --> 01:10:08,781
and made those walls dissolve away.

961
01:10:08,865 --> 01:10:11,200
And for the briefest of moments...

962
01:10:11,284 --> 01:10:14,370
every last man at Shawshank felt free.

963
01:10:16,873 --> 01:10:19,375
It pissed the Warden off something awful.

964
01:10:20,794 --> 01:10:21,919
Open the door.

965
01:10:24,673 --> 01:10:26,590
Open it up!

966
01:10:27,801 --> 01:10:30,177
Dufresne, open this door!

967
01:10:31,805 --> 01:10:33,138
Turn that off!

968
01:10:39,939 --> 01:10:42,691
I am warning you, Dufresne. Turn that off!

969
01:10:56,539 --> 01:10:58,415
Dufresne...

970
01:10:59,542 --> 01:11:01,626
You're mine now.

971
01:11:09,176 --> 01:11:11,928
Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

972
01:11:12,013 --> 01:11:14,431
On your feet!

973
01:11:15,641 --> 01:11:17,726
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

974
01:11:19,228 --> 01:11:23,273
Y- Y-You couldn't play something good, huh?
Hank Williams or something?

975
01:11:23,357 --> 01:11:26,026
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

976
01:11:26,110 --> 01:11:27,903
Was it worth it, two weeks in the hole?

977
01:11:27,987 --> 01:11:29,237
Easiest time I ever did.

978
01:11:29,322 --> 01:11:32,365
Bullshit!
There's no such thing as easy time in the hole.

979
01:11:32,366 --> 01:11:34,993
A week in the hole is like a year.

980
01:11:35,077 --> 01:11:37,788
I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

981
01:11:37,873 --> 01:11:41,208
So, they let you tote that record player
down there, huh?

982
01:11:43,337 --> 01:11:44,962
It was in here.

983
01:11:45,047 --> 01:11:46,714
And in here.

984
01:11:47,925 --> 01:11:52,178
That's the beauty of music.
They can't get that from you.

985
01:11:56,099 --> 01:11:58,601
Haven't you ever felt that way about music?

986
01:12:00,270 --> 01:12:04,357
Well, I played a mean harmonica,
as a younger man.

987
01:12:04,441 --> 01:12:06,233
Lost interest in it, though.

988
01:12:06,318 --> 01:12:08,152
Didn't make much sense in here.

989
01:12:08,236 --> 01:12:10,696
Here's where it makes the most sense.

990
01:12:10,781 --> 01:12:13,366
You need it, so you don't forget.

991
01:12:13,450 --> 01:12:14,784
Forget?

992
01:12:14,868 --> 01:12:16,827
Forget that...

993
01:12:16,912 --> 01:12:18,996
there are places...

994
01:12:20,332 --> 01:12:22,875
..in the world that aren't made out of stone...

995
01:12:22,960 --> 01:12:25,002
that there's a...

996
01:12:25,087 --> 01:12:26,921
there's something...

997
01:12:27,005 --> 01:12:29,799
inside that they can't get to...

998
01:12:29,883 --> 01:12:32,176
that they can't touch.

999
01:12:32,260 --> 01:12:34,137
It's yours.

1000
01:12:35,556 --> 01:12:37,265
What are you talking about?

1001
01:12:38,351 --> 01:12:39,935
Hope.

1002
01:12:40,019 --> 01:12:41,895
Hope?

1003
01:12:43,731 --> 01:12:46,400
Let me tell you something, my friend.

1004
01:12:46,484 --> 01:12:48,443
Hope is a dangerous thing.

1005
01:12:50,029 --> 01:12:52,072
Hope can drive a man insane.

1006
01:12:53,116 --> 01:12:55,033
It's got no use on the inside.

1007
01:12:55,118 --> 01:12:57,786
You'd better get used to that idea.

1008
01:13:00,206 --> 01:13:01,832
Like Brooks did?

1009
01:13:27,066 --> 01:13:28,108
Sit down.

1010
01:13:33,323 --> 01:13:36,784
It says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

1011
01:13:36,869 --> 01:13:39,495
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1012
01:13:39,580 --> 01:13:41,664
Oh, yes, sir.

1013
01:13:41,665 --> 01:13:43,750
Without a doubt.

1014
01:13:44,793 --> 01:13:47,128
And I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

1015
01:13:49,715 --> 01:13:51,758
No danger to society here.

1016
01:13:51,842 --> 01:13:53,926
God's honest truth.

1017
01:13:56,263 --> 01:13:58,347
Absolutely rehabilitated.

1018
01:14:08,275 --> 01:14:10,359
30 years.

1019
01:14:11,445 --> 01:14:13,488
Jesus, when they say it like that...

1020
01:14:13,572 --> 01:14:15,656
You wonder where it went.

1021
01:14:18,619 --> 01:14:20,703
I wonder where ten years went.

1022
01:14:25,751 --> 01:14:27,043
Here.

1023
01:14:27,127 --> 01:14:29,295
Little parole rejection present.

1024
01:14:31,132 --> 01:14:33,175
Go ahead and open it.

1025
01:14:33,259 --> 01:14:37,054
I had to go through one of your competitors.
I hope you don't mind.

1026
01:14:37,138 --> 01:14:39,223
I wanted it to be a surprise.

1027
01:14:49,359 --> 01:14:51,443
It's very pretty, Andy.

1028
01:14:52,529 --> 01:14:54,613
Thank you.

1029
01:14:56,366 --> 01:14:58,450
Are you going to play it?

1030
01:15:02,580 --> 01:15:04,665
No.

1031
01:15:06,960 --> 01:15:09,044
Not right now.

1032
01:15:16,302 --> 01:15:18,387
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1033
01:15:19,430 --> 01:15:21,473
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1034
01:15:21,558 --> 01:15:23,642
Tier 1 South. Clear.

1035
01:15:26,479 --> 01:15:28,565
Fall in!

1036
01:16:03,142 --> 01:16:04,726
Lights out!

1037
01:16:39,638 --> 01:16:41,680
Andy was as good as his word.

1038
01:16:41,765 --> 01:16:44,266
He wrote two letters a week instead of one.

1039
01:16:46,895 --> 01:16:51,023
In 1959, the State Senate
finally clued into the fact

1040
01:16:51,107 --> 01:16:53,984
they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.

1041
01:16:54,069 --> 01:17:00,658
Appropriations Committee voted
an annual payment of $500 just to shut him up.

1042
01:17:00,742 --> 01:17:02,451
And you'd be amazed

1043
01:17:02,535 --> 01:17:04,203
how far Andy could stretch it.

1044
01:17:04,287 --> 01:17:07,164
He made deals with book clubs, charity groups.

1045
01:17:07,249 --> 01:17:09,625
He bought remaindered books by the pound.

1046
01:17:09,709 --> 01:17:11,919
Treasure Island.

1047
01:17:12,003 --> 01:17:14,171
Robert Louis...

1048
01:17:14,256 --> 01:17:15,464
..Stevenson.

1049
01:17:15,548 --> 01:17:17,007
Fiction, adventure.

1050
01:17:19,010 --> 01:17:20,636
What's next?

1051
01:17:20,637 --> 01:17:23,347
I got here Auto Repair and...

1052
01:17:24,392 --> 01:17:25,725
..Soap Carving.

1053
01:17:25,810 --> 01:17:29,187
Trade skills and hobbies. Goes under
Educational. The stack behind you.

1054
01:17:29,272 --> 01:17:31,314
The Count Of Monte Crisco.

1055
01:17:31,399 --> 01:17:33,733
That's Cristo, you dumb shit.

1056
01:17:33,818 --> 01:17:37,612
By Alexandree...Dumass.

1057
01:17:37,697 --> 01:17:42,617
Dumb-ass?

1058
01:17:45,121 --> 01:17:47,455
Dumas. You know what that's about?

1059
01:17:47,540 --> 01:17:48,915
Uh-uh.

1060
01:17:49,000 --> 01:17:51,710
You'll like it. It's about a prison break.

1061
01:17:51,794 --> 01:17:55,797
We ought to file that under Educational, too,
oughtn't we?

1062
01:17:55,881 --> 01:18:00,051
The rest of us did our best to pitch in
when and where we could.

1063
01:18:01,304 --> 01:18:03,138
By the year Kennedy was shot,

1064
01:18:03,222 --> 01:18:07,559
Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of rat turds and turpentine

1065
01:18:07,560 --> 01:18:10,895
into the best prison library in New England,

1066
01:18:10,980 --> 01:18:14,858
complete with a fine selection of Hank Williams.

1067
01:18:14,942 --> 01:18:19,112
# Lawd I don't know what I'll do-ooo

1068
01:18:19,196 --> 01:18:21,948
# All I do is sit and sigh...

1069
01:18:22,033 --> 01:18:26,787
That was also the year Warden Norton
instituted his famous Inside Out program.

1070
01:18:26,872 --> 01:18:29,582
You may remember reading about it.

1071
01:18:29,666 --> 01:18:33,085
It made all the papers
and got his picture in Look Magazine.

1072
01:18:33,170 --> 01:18:34,837
No free ride.

1073
01:18:34,921 --> 01:18:37,882
But rather a genuine, progressive advance

1074
01:18:37,966 --> 01:18:40,134
in corrections and rehabilitation.

1075
01:18:41,178 --> 01:18:43,512
Our inmates, properly supervised,

1076
01:18:43,597 --> 01:18:46,349
will be put to work outside these walls,

1077
01:18:46,433 --> 01:18:48,517
performing all manner of public service.

1078
01:18:48,602 --> 01:18:52,521
These men can learn
the value of an honest day's labor,

1079
01:18:52,606 --> 01:18:56,275
while providing a valuable service
to the community and...

1080
01:18:56,360 --> 01:19:01,572
at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. and Mrs. John Q Taxpayer.

1081
01:19:01,656 --> 01:19:04,325
Of course,
Norton failed to mention to the press

1082
01:19:04,409 --> 01:19:07,703
that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

1083
01:19:07,788 --> 01:19:10,956
There are a hundred different ways
to skim off the top.

1084
01:19:11,041 --> 01:19:13,667
Men, materials, you name it.

1085
01:19:14,711 --> 01:19:17,463
And, oh, my Lord, how the money rolled in.

1086
01:19:17,547 --> 01:19:19,673
If this keeps up, you'll put me out of business.

1087
01:19:19,758 --> 01:19:21,927
- Ned!
- This pool of slave labor you've got,

1088
01:19:22,011 --> 01:19:24,054
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1089
01:19:24,138 --> 01:19:28,100
Ned, we're providing
a valuable community service here.

1090
01:19:28,184 --> 01:19:30,435
Well, that's fine for the papers

1091
01:19:30,520 --> 01:19:32,020
but I've got a family to feed.

1092
01:19:32,105 --> 01:19:33,814
Sam...

1093
01:19:33,898 --> 01:19:36,358
Sam, we go back a long way.

1094
01:19:36,442 --> 01:19:38,777
I need this new highway contract.

1095
01:19:38,861 --> 01:19:41,071
I don't get it, and I go under.

1096
01:19:41,155 --> 01:19:43,198
That's a fact.

1097
01:19:43,282 --> 01:19:45,367
You just have some of this fine pie

1098
01:19:45,451 --> 01:19:47,494
my missus made especially for you,

1099
01:19:47,578 --> 01:19:48,912
and you think about that.

1100
01:19:56,963 --> 01:19:59,881
Ned, I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1101
01:19:59,966 --> 01:20:03,176
It seems to me I already got
my boys committed elsewhere.

1102
01:20:05,054 --> 01:20:07,639
You be sure and thank Maisie for this fine pie.

1103
01:20:09,267 --> 01:20:11,435
And behind every shady deal,

1104
01:20:11,519 --> 01:20:13,728
behind every dollar earned,

1105
01:20:13,813 --> 01:20:16,982
there was Andy, keeping the books.

1106
01:20:18,025 --> 01:20:21,446
Two deposits.
Maine National and New England First.

1107
01:20:21,530 --> 01:20:23,614
Night drops as always, sir.

1108
01:20:54,021 --> 01:20:55,771
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1109
01:20:55,856 --> 01:20:58,649
- Two suits for dry-clean and a bag of whatnot.
- Yes, sir.

1110
01:20:58,734 --> 01:21:02,487
Tell them if they over-starch my shirts again,
they'll hear about it from me.

1111
01:21:02,571 --> 01:21:04,572
How do I look?

1112
01:21:04,656 --> 01:21:07,366
- Very nice, sir.
- Big charity to-do up Portland way.

1113
01:21:07,451 --> 01:21:09,160
The Governor's going to be there.

1114
01:21:10,579 --> 01:21:12,622
Want the rest of this?

1115
01:21:12,706 --> 01:21:14,790
The woman can't bake worth shit.

1116
01:21:16,168 --> 01:21:17,961
Thank you, sir.

1117
01:21:20,131 --> 01:21:23,884
- He's got his fingers in a lot of pies, I hear.
- What you hear isn't half of it.

1118
01:21:23,968 --> 01:21:26,428
He's got scams you haven't even dreamed of.

1119
01:21:26,513 --> 01:21:28,555
Kickbacks on his kickbacks.

1120
01:21:28,640 --> 01:21:31,517
There's a river of dirty money
running through this place.

1121
01:21:31,601 --> 01:21:34,853
But the problem with having all that money
is you'll have to explain

1122
01:21:34,938 --> 01:21:37,523
- where it came from.
- That's where I come in.

1123
01:21:37,607 --> 01:21:40,108
I channel it, filter it, funnel it.

1124
01:21:40,193 --> 01:21:42,736
Stocks, securities, tax-free municipals.

1125
01:21:42,820 --> 01:21:45,489
I send that money out into the real world.

1126
01:21:45,573 --> 01:21:49,201
- And when it comes back...
- Clean as a virgin's honey pot, huh?

1127
01:21:49,285 --> 01:21:50,494
Cleaner.

1128
01:21:50,578 --> 01:21:54,206
By the time Norton retires,
I'll have made him a millionaire.

1129
01:21:56,960 --> 01:22:01,380
If they ever catch on, though, he's gonna
wind up in here wearing a number himself.

1130
01:22:01,464 --> 01:22:04,716
Now, Red, I thought you had
a little more faith in me than that.

1131
01:22:04,801 --> 01:22:08,095
I know you're good, Andy,
but all that paper leaves a trail.

1132
01:22:08,179 --> 01:22:11,181
Now, anybody gets curious,
the FBI, the IRS, whatever,

1133
01:22:11,266 --> 01:22:14,101
it's gonna lead to somebody.

1134
01:22:14,185 --> 01:22:16,145
Sure it is. But not to me.

1135
01:22:16,230 --> 01:22:18,231
And certainly not to the Warden.

1136
01:22:22,278 --> 01:22:23,570
All right. Who?

1137
01:22:23,654 --> 01:22:25,363
Randall Stevens.

1138
01:22:25,447 --> 01:22:26,614
Who?

1139
01:22:27,700 --> 01:22:32,412
The silent silent partner. He's the guilty one,
Your Honor. The man with the bank accounts.

1140
01:22:32,496 --> 01:22:34,664
That's where the filtering process starts.

1141
01:22:34,748 --> 01:22:37,917
If they trace anything,
it's just going to lead to him.

1142
01:22:38,002 --> 01:22:39,586
But who is he?

1143
01:22:39,670 --> 01:22:41,713
He's a phantom, an apparition.

1144
01:22:41,797 --> 01:22:43,756
Second cousin to Harvey the Rabbit.

1145
01:22:43,841 --> 01:22:46,009
I conjured him...

1146
01:22:46,093 --> 01:22:48,136
out of thin air.

1147
01:22:48,220 --> 01:22:51,055
He doesn't exist, except on paper.

1148
01:22:54,184 --> 01:22:56,561
Andy, you canâ€™t just make a person up.

1149
01:22:56,645 --> 01:22:59,772
Sure you can, if you know how
the system works, where the cracks are.

1150
01:22:59,857 --> 01:23:03,359
It's amazing what you can accomplish by mail.

1151
01:23:03,444 --> 01:23:06,070
Mr. Stevens has a birth certificate,

1152
01:23:06,155 --> 01:23:08,489
a driver's license, social security number.

1153
01:23:08,574 --> 01:23:09,782
You're shitting me?

1154
01:23:09,867 --> 01:23:11,826
If they ever trace any of those accounts,

1155
01:23:11,910 --> 01:23:14,788
they're going to wind up chasing
a figment of my imagination.

1156
01:23:14,873 --> 01:23:16,957
Well, I'll be damned.

1157
01:23:18,251 --> 01:23:20,294
Did I say you were good?

1158
01:23:20,378 --> 01:23:22,546
Shit, you're a Rembrandt!

1159
01:23:22,631 --> 01:23:24,673
You know, the funny thing is,

1160
01:23:24,758 --> 01:23:28,719
on the outside, I was an honest man,
straight as an arrow.

1161
01:23:29,763 --> 01:23:32,139
I had to come to prison to be a crook.

1162
01:23:40,899 --> 01:23:42,274
Ever bother you?

1163
01:23:43,318 --> 01:23:46,737
I don't run the scams, Red,
I just process the profits.

1164
01:23:46,821 --> 01:23:48,864
Fine line maybe but...

1165
01:23:48,948 --> 01:23:51,659
I also built that library

1166
01:23:51,743 --> 01:23:54,370
and used it to help a dozen guys
get a high school diploma.

1167
01:23:54,454 --> 01:23:56,330
Why do you think the Warden lets me do it?

1168
01:23:56,414 --> 01:23:59,166
To keep you happy and doing the laundry.

1169
01:23:59,250 --> 01:24:01,377
Money instead of sheets.

1170
01:24:01,461 --> 01:24:04,171
Well, I work cheap. That's the trade-off.

1171
01:24:09,761 --> 01:24:11,971
Willy And The Hand Jive

1172
01:24:19,772 --> 01:24:21,564
# I know a cat named...

1173
01:24:21,649 --> 01:24:24,317
Tommy Williams
came to Shawshank in 1965

1174
01:24:24,402 --> 01:24:26,444
on a two-year stretch for B&E.

1175
01:24:26,529 --> 01:24:28,655
That's breaking and entering to you.

1176
01:24:28,739 --> 01:24:33,368
The cops caught him sneaking TV sets
out the back door of a JC Penney.

1177
01:24:33,452 --> 01:24:35,203
Young punk.

1178
01:24:35,287 --> 01:24:37,330
Mr. Rock'n'roll.

1179
01:24:37,415 --> 01:24:39,082
Cocky as hell.

1180
01:24:39,166 --> 01:24:41,751
Hey, come on, old boys! Moving like molasses!

1181
01:24:41,836 --> 01:24:43,795
Making me look bad.

1182
01:24:43,796 --> 01:24:45,755
We liked him immediately.

1183
01:24:45,840 --> 01:24:47,882
So I'm backing out the door, right?

1184
01:24:47,967 --> 01:24:49,676
And I got the TV like this.

1185
01:24:49,760 --> 01:24:53,596
It was a big old thing. I couldn't see shit.
Suddenly, I hears this voice.

1186
01:24:53,681 --> 01:24:55,724
"Freeze, kid! Hands in the air."

1187
01:24:55,808 --> 01:24:57,475
Well, I just stand there,

1188
01:24:57,560 --> 01:25:00,353
holding onto that TV.
So, finally, the voice says,

1189
01:25:00,438 --> 01:25:02,397
"Do you hear what I said, boy?"

1190
01:25:02,481 --> 01:25:04,858
I say, "Yes, sir, I sure did.

1191
01:25:04,942 --> 01:25:08,570
But if I drop this fucking thing,
you got me on destruction of property, too."

1192
01:25:12,659 --> 01:25:15,369
Hey, you've done a stretch in Cashman, right?

1193
01:25:15,454 --> 01:25:19,290
Yeah. Yeah, that was an easy piece of time,
let me tell you.

1194
01:25:19,374 --> 01:25:22,001
Weekend furloughs, work programs.

1195
01:25:22,085 --> 01:25:23,502
Not like here.

1196
01:25:23,587 --> 01:25:25,921
Sounds like you done time
all over New England.

1197
01:25:26,006 --> 01:25:31,093
Yeah, I've been in and out since I was 13. You
name the place, chances are I've been there.

1198
01:25:31,178 --> 01:25:35,181
Perhaps it's time you tried a new profession?

1199
01:25:35,265 --> 01:25:40,352
What I mean is, you don't seem to be a good
thief. Maybe you should try something else.

1200
01:25:40,437 --> 01:25:44,273
Yeah, well, what the hell
do you know about it, Capone?

1201
01:25:44,357 --> 01:25:46,108
What are you in for?

1202
01:25:46,193 --> 01:25:47,818
Me?

1203
01:25:49,321 --> 01:25:51,405
The lawyer fucked me.

1204
01:25:55,118 --> 01:25:58,537
Everybody's innocent in here.
Don't you know that?

1205
01:26:06,004 --> 01:26:10,175
As it turned out, Tommy had himself
a young wife and a new baby girl.

1206
01:26:11,219 --> 01:26:13,783
Maybe it was the thought of them on the streets

1207
01:26:13,784 --> 01:26:16,348
or his child growing up not knowing her daddy.

1208
01:26:16,432 --> 01:26:20,268
Whatever it was,
something lit a fire under that boy's ass.

1209
01:26:24,232 --> 01:26:27,484
I was thinking of maybe
trying for my high school equivalency.

1210
01:26:27,568 --> 01:26:30,153
I hear you helped a couple of fellas with that.

1211
01:26:31,364 --> 01:26:33,573
I don't waste time on losers, Tommy.

1212
01:26:35,159 --> 01:26:37,244
I ain't no goddamn loser.

1213
01:26:39,080 --> 01:26:41,164
- You mean that?
- Yeah.

1214
01:26:42,834 --> 01:26:44,876
You really mean that?

1215
01:26:44,961 --> 01:26:46,628
Yes, sir, I do.

1216
01:26:46,712 --> 01:26:48,839
Good. Because if we do this,

1217
01:26:48,923 --> 01:26:51,675
we do it all the way, 100%, nothing half-assed.

1218
01:26:52,802 --> 01:26:54,886
The thing is, see...

1219
01:26:56,055 --> 01:26:57,889
..I don't read so good.

1220
01:26:59,016 --> 01:27:00,225
Well.

1221
01:27:01,978 --> 01:27:04,020
You don't read...

1222
01:27:04,105 --> 01:27:06,190
so well.

1223
01:27:07,651 --> 01:27:09,318
We'll get to that.

1224
01:27:10,404 --> 01:27:12,154
- R.
- R...

1225
01:27:12,239 --> 01:27:13,614
- S.
- S...

1226
01:27:13,699 --> 01:27:15,867
So Andy took Tommy under his wing.

1227
01:27:15,951 --> 01:27:18,369
He started walking him through his ABCs.

1228
01:27:20,038 --> 01:27:22,623
Tommy took to it pretty well, too.

1229
01:27:22,708 --> 01:27:25,668
The boy found brains he never knew he had.

1230
01:27:28,005 --> 01:27:31,799
Before long, Andy started him
on his course requirements.

1231
01:27:31,884 --> 01:27:33,843
He really liked the kid.

1232
01:27:33,927 --> 01:27:37,096
It gave him a thrill to help a youngster
crawl off the shit heap.

1233
01:27:38,140 --> 01:27:40,182
But that wasn't the only reason.

1234
01:27:40,267 --> 01:27:42,727
Prison time is slow time.

1235
01:27:43,770 --> 01:27:46,022
So you do what you can to keep going.

1236
01:27:46,106 --> 01:27:48,357
Some fellas collect stamps.

1237
01:27:48,358 --> 01:27:50,985
Others build matchstick houses.

1238
01:27:52,029 --> 01:27:54,405
Andy built a library.

1239
01:27:55,449 --> 01:27:57,491
Now he needed a new project.

1240
01:27:57,576 --> 01:27:59,619
Tommy was it.

1241
01:27:59,703 --> 01:28:03,916
It was the same reason he spent years
shaping and polishing those rocks.

1242
01:28:04,000 --> 01:28:07,628
The same reason
he hung his fantasy girlies on the wall.

1243
01:28:09,005 --> 01:28:10,505
In prison,

1244
01:28:10,590 --> 01:28:13,717
a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1245
01:28:15,178 --> 01:28:19,640
By 1966, right about the time
Tommy was getting ready to take his exams,

1246
01:28:19,641 --> 01:28:21,683
it was lovely Raquel.

1247
01:28:38,952 --> 01:28:39,993
Time.

1248
01:28:46,000 --> 01:28:47,292
Well?

1249
01:28:48,378 --> 01:28:49,920
Well, it's for shit.

1250
01:28:50,004 --> 01:28:52,506
I wasted a whole fucking year of my time

1251
01:28:52,590 --> 01:28:55,759
- with this bullshit.
- It's probably not as bad as you think.

1252
01:28:55,843 --> 01:28:59,554
It's worse. I didn't get one thing right.
It might as well have been in Chinese.

1253
01:28:59,639 --> 01:29:02,141
Let's see how the score comes out.

1254
01:29:02,226 --> 01:29:04,852
Well, I'll tell you how the goddamn score
comes out.

1255
01:29:06,647 --> 01:29:08,564
Two points right there.

1256
01:29:08,649 --> 01:29:10,441
There's your goddamn score!

1257
01:29:10,526 --> 01:29:14,362
Goddamn cats crawling up trees,
5x5 is 25.

1258
01:29:15,447 --> 01:29:16,990
Fuck this place!

1259
01:29:16,991 --> 01:29:18,282
Fuck it!

1260
01:29:37,094 --> 01:29:39,846
I feel bad. I let him down.

1261
01:29:39,930 --> 01:29:42,015
Ah, that's crap, kid.

1262
