01:46:57,860 --> 01:46:59,903
Promise me, Red,

1516
01:46:59,987 --> 01:47:01,988
if you ever get out,

1517
01:47:02,073 --> 01:47:04,115
find that spot.

1518
01:47:05,159 --> 01:47:07,890
At the base of that
wall, you'll find a rock that

1519
01:47:07,891 --> 01:47:10,622
has no earthly business in a Maine hayfield.

1520
01:47:10,706 --> 01:47:13,208
A piece of black, volcanic glass.

1521
01:47:16,378 --> 01:47:19,172
There's something buried under it
I want you to have.

1522
01:47:19,256 --> 01:47:21,257
What, Andy?

1523
01:47:21,342 --> 01:47:23,426
What's buried under there?

1524
01:47:25,222 --> 01:47:28,599
You'll have to pry it up to see.

1525
01:47:33,939 --> 01:47:36,023
No, I'm telling you, the guy is...

1526
01:47:37,067 --> 01:47:39,151
He's talking funnier.

1527
01:47:39,236 --> 01:47:42,613
- I'm really worried about him.
- We ought to keep an eye on him.

1528
01:47:42,697 --> 01:47:46,742
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's got that cell all to himself.

1529
01:47:47,828 --> 01:47:49,286
Oh, Lord.

1530
01:47:49,371 --> 01:47:51,413
What?

1531
01:47:53,083 --> 01:47:55,417
Andy come down to the loading dock today.

1532
01:47:55,502 --> 01:47:59,004
- He asked me for a length of rope.
- Rope?

1533
01:47:59,089 --> 01:48:00,923
Six feet long.

1534
01:48:01,007 --> 01:48:02,466
And you gave it to him?

1535
01:48:02,551 --> 01:48:05,219
Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?

1536
01:48:05,220 --> 01:48:06,929
Jesus, Heywood.

1537
01:48:07,013 --> 01:48:09,265
Hey, how the hell was I supposed to know?

1538
01:48:09,349 --> 01:48:11,267
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1539
01:48:11,351 --> 01:48:12,393
No.

1540
01:48:13,436 --> 01:48:15,646
Andy would never do that.

1541
01:48:15,647 --> 01:48:17,731
Never.

1542
01:48:18,775 --> 01:48:20,860
I don't know.

1543
01:48:22,905 --> 01:48:24,990
Every man has his breaking point.

1544
01:48:27,618 --> 01:48:28,869
Lickety-split.

1545
01:48:28,953 --> 01:48:31,830
- I want to get home.
- Just about finished, sir.

1546
01:48:47,930 --> 01:48:50,015
Three deposits tonight.

1547
01:48:58,399 --> 01:49:00,483
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1548
01:49:00,484 --> 01:49:03,945
And shine my shoes.
I want 'em looking like mirrors.

1549
01:49:04,030 --> 01:49:05,405
Yes, sir.

1550
01:49:10,703 --> 01:49:12,370
It's good having you back, Andy.

1551
01:49:12,455 --> 01:49:15,207
The place wasn't the same without you.

1552
01:50:02,256 --> 01:50:05,007
Lights out!

1553
01:50:35,748 --> 01:50:38,041
I've had some long nights in stir.

1554
01:50:39,085 --> 01:50:41,795
Alone in the dark with
nothing but your thoughts,

1555
01:50:41,879 --> 01:50:43,714
time can draw out like a blade.

1556
01:50:50,096 --> 01:50:52,431
That was the longest night of my life.

1557
01:51:08,573 --> 01:51:10,198
Give me a count.

1558
01:51:14,537 --> 01:51:16,580
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1559
01:51:16,664 --> 01:51:17,999
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1560
01:51:18,083 --> 01:51:21,669
- Tier 3 North. Clear.
- Man missing on Tier 2.

1561
01:51:21,754 --> 01:51:24,839
- Cell 245.
- Dufresne.

1562
01:51:24,923 --> 01:51:27,842
Get your ass out here, boy.
You're holding up the show.

1563
01:51:30,346 --> 01:51:34,390
Don't make me come down there.
I'll thump your skull for you.

1564
01:51:41,982 --> 01:51:45,360
Damn it, Dufresne, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1565
01:51:45,444 --> 01:51:48,529
You'd better be sick or dead in there,
I shit you not!

1566
01:51:48,614 --> 01:51:50,448
You hear me?

1567
01:51:56,955 --> 01:51:59,040
Oh, my holy God.

1568
01:52:15,892 --> 01:52:18,602
I want every man on this cell block questioned.

1569
01:52:18,603 --> 01:52:20,813
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1570
01:52:20,897 --> 01:52:22,106
Him!

1571
01:52:24,025 --> 01:52:26,110
Open 237.

1572
01:52:29,114 --> 01:52:31,240
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1573
01:52:31,324 --> 01:52:32,866
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1574
01:52:32,951 --> 01:52:35,202
Don't say that to me again.

1575
01:52:35,286 --> 01:52:36,370
But, sir, he wasn't.

1576
01:52:36,454 --> 01:52:38,622
I can see that, Haig!

1577
01:52:38,706 --> 01:52:40,499
You think I'm blind?

1578
01:52:40,500 --> 01:52:43,627
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1579
01:52:43,711 --> 01:52:44,711
No, sir.

1580
01:52:44,796 --> 01:52:46,839
What about you?

1581
01:52:46,923 --> 01:52:48,757
Are you blind?

1582
01:52:48,842 --> 01:52:51,385
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1583
01:52:51,469 --> 01:52:54,763
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. See? Right there.

1584
01:52:54,848 --> 01:52:56,723
Dufresne.

1585
01:52:57,976 --> 01:52:59,643
He was in his cell at lights out.

1586
01:52:59,727 --> 01:53:02,938
It stands to reason
he'd still be here in the morning.

1587
01:53:04,023 --> 01:53:05,899
I want him found.

1588
01:53:05,984 --> 01:53:08,569
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast.

1589
01:53:08,653 --> 01:53:09,695
Now!

1590
01:53:09,696 --> 01:53:11,196
Yes, sir!

1591
01:53:12,323 --> 01:53:14,909
Let's go, let's go!
Move your butts! Move it!

1592
01:53:17,746 --> 01:53:18,788
Stand.

1593
01:53:19,915 --> 01:53:21,166
Well?

1594
01:53:24,545 --> 01:53:25,670
Well, what?

1595
01:53:25,754 --> 01:53:29,215
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1596
01:53:30,259 --> 01:53:31,885
He must have said something.

1597
01:53:31,969 --> 01:53:34,012
No, sir, Warden.

1598
01:53:34,096 --> 01:53:35,555
Not a word.

1599
01:53:37,558 --> 01:53:39,559
Lord, it's a miracle!

1600
01:53:40,603 --> 01:53:43,062
A man up and vanished like a fart in the wind.

1601
01:53:43,147 --> 01:53:44,898
Nothing left but...

1602
01:53:44,982 --> 01:53:47,901
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1603
01:53:47,985 --> 01:53:49,736
And that cupcake on the wall.

1604
01:53:49,820 --> 01:53:51,446
Let's ask her.

1605
01:53:51,530 --> 01:53:55,492
Maybe she knows. What say there,
Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1606
01:53:56,577 --> 01:53:57,660
Ah...

1607
01:53:57,661 --> 01:53:59,120
I guess not.

1608
01:53:59,205 --> 01:54:02,081
Why should she be any different?

1609
01:54:02,166 --> 01:54:04,626
This is a conspiracy.

1610
01:54:04,710 --> 01:54:06,920
That's what this is.

1611
01:54:07,004 --> 01:54:08,546
One big...

1612
01:54:08,631 --> 01:54:11,383
damn conspiracy!

1613
01:54:11,468 --> 01:54:14,136
And everyone's in on it!

1614
01:54:14,221 --> 01:54:15,513
Including her!

1615
01:54:50,173 --> 01:54:52,049
In 1966,

1616
01:54:52,133 --> 01:54:54,802
Andy Dufresne escaped

1617
01:54:54,886 --> 01:54:56,971
from Shawshank Prison.

1618
01:54:58,640 --> 01:55:01,392
All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes,

1619
01:55:01,476 --> 01:55:03,519
a bar of soap

1620
01:55:03,603 --> 01:55:07,982
and an old rock hammer
damn near worn down to the nub.

1621
01:55:12,363 --> 01:55:17,200
I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1622
01:55:17,285 --> 01:55:19,995
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1623
01:55:38,556 --> 01:55:40,640
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1624
01:55:41,684 --> 01:55:45,186
I imagine it appealed to his meticulous nature.

1625
01:55:45,271 --> 01:55:47,564
An Ice Age here,

1626
01:55:47,648 --> 01:55:50,233
a million years of mountain-building there.

1627
01:55:51,277 --> 01:55:53,695
Geology is the study of pressure and time.

1628
01:55:54,905 --> 01:55:56,948
That's all it takes, really.

1629
01:55:57,033 --> 01:55:59,075
Pressure...

1630
01:55:59,160 --> 01:56:01,036
and time.

1631
01:56:01,120 --> 01:56:04,456
That and a big goddamn poster.

1632
01:56:07,669 --> 01:56:09,045
Like I said,

1633
01:56:09,046 --> 01:56:12,840
in prison, a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1634
01:56:15,636 --> 01:56:20,806
It turns out Andy's favorite hobby
was toting his wall out into the exercise yard.

1635
01:56:20,891 --> 01:56:22,975
A handful at a time.

1636
01:56:24,811 --> 01:56:26,979
I guess after Tommy was killed,

1637
01:56:27,064 --> 01:56:29,899
Andy decided he'd been here
just about long enough.

1638
01:56:29,983 --> 01:56:32,193
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1639
01:56:33,487 --> 01:56:35,571
I'm just about finished, sir.

1640
01:56:56,968 --> 01:56:59,053
Three deposits tonight.

1641
01:57:06,229 --> 01:57:08,271
Andy did like he was told.

1642
01:57:09,315 --> 01:57:12,818
Buffed those shoes to a high mirror shine.

1643
01:57:16,406 --> 01:57:18,448
The guard simply didn't notice.

1644
01:57:18,533 --> 01:57:20,575
Neither did I.

1645
01:57:20,660 --> 01:57:24,996
I mean, seriously, how often
do you really look at a man's shoes?

1646
01:59:29,040 --> 01:59:35,212
Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards
of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.

1647
01:59:36,548 --> 01:59:38,549
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1648
01:59:43,263 --> 01:59:45,472
500 yards.

1649
01:59:46,516 --> 01:59:49,017
That's the length of five football fields.

1650
01:59:50,061 --> 01:59:52,312
Just shy of half a mile.

1651
02:00:47,536 --> 02:00:52,081
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret,

1652
02:00:52,166 --> 02:00:55,585
a man nobody ever laid eyes on before

1653
02:00:55,669 --> 02:00:58,088
strode into the Maine National Bank.

1654
02:00:58,173 --> 02:01:00,215
Until that moment,

1655
02:01:00,300 --> 02:01:02,176
he didn't exist,

1656
02:01:02,260 --> 02:01:03,594
except on paper.

1657
02:01:03,678 --> 02:01:04,720
May I help you?

1658
02:01:04,804 --> 02:01:06,847
He had all the proper ID,

1659
02:01:06,932 --> 02:01:10,559
driver's license, birth certificate,
social security card.

1660
02:01:10,644 --> 02:01:13,938
And the signature was a spot-on match.

1661
02:01:14,022 --> 02:01:17,066
I must say, I'm sorry
to be losing your business.

1662
02:01:17,150 --> 02:01:19,151
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1663
02:01:19,235 --> 02:01:21,028
Thank you.

1664
02:01:21,112 --> 02:01:22,905
I'm sure I will.

1665
02:01:22,989 --> 02:01:25,115
Here's your cashier's check, sir.

1666
02:01:25,200 --> 02:01:27,242
Will there be anything else?

1667
02:01:27,327 --> 02:01:28,327
Please...

1668
02:01:28,411 --> 02:01:31,497
Would you add this to your outgoing mail?

1669
02:01:31,581 --> 02:01:33,791
I'd be happy to.

1670
02:01:33,875 --> 02:01:36,210
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

1671
02:01:36,294 --> 02:01:41,090
Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.

1672
02:01:42,258 --> 02:01:48,722
All told, he blew town with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1673
02:01:48,807 --> 02:01:51,266
Severance pay for 19 years.

1674
02:01:59,402 --> 02:02:01,695
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1675
02:02:54,416 --> 02:02:57,418
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1676
02:02:57,502 --> 02:02:59,816
If you give up the right
to remain silent, anything

1677
02:02:59,817 --> 02:03:02,131
you say will be held against you in court.

1678
02:03:02,215 --> 02:03:04,091
I wasn't there to see it.

1679
02:03:04,176 --> 02:03:09,055
But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing
like a little girl when they took him away.

1680
02:03:14,478 --> 02:03:17,271
Norton had no intention of going that quietly.

1681
02:03:33,246 --> 02:03:34,705
Samuel Norton?

1682
02:03:34,790 --> 02:03:38,042
We have a warrant for your arrest. Open up.

1683
02:03:40,921 --> 02:03:42,046
Norton!

1684
02:03:42,130 --> 02:03:43,798
Open the door.

1685
02:03:43,882 --> 02:03:45,633
I'm not sure which key it is.

1686
02:03:48,512 --> 02:03:50,179
Norton!

1687
02:03:55,645 --> 02:03:57,729
Make it easy on yourself, Norton.

1688
02:04:09,033 --> 02:04:12,619
I like to think
the last thing that went through his head,

1689
02:04:12,703 --> 02:04:14,412
other than that bullet,

1690
02:04:14,497 --> 02:04:18,500
was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1691
02:04:20,169 --> 02:04:21,253
Carter, James...

1692
02:04:21,337 --> 02:04:24,714
Not long after the Warden
deprived us of his company,

1693
02:04:24,799 --> 02:04:27,050
I got a postcard in the mail.

1694
02:04:28,761 --> 02:04:31,179
It was blank but the postmark said...

1695
02:04:31,264 --> 02:04:34,015
Fort Hancock, Texas.

1696
02:04:34,100 --> 02:04:36,143
Fort Hancock.

1697
02:04:36,227 --> 02:04:38,270
Right on the border.

1698
02:04:38,354 --> 02:04:40,397
That's where Andy crossed.

1699
02:04:40,481 --> 02:04:44,359
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down,

1700
02:04:45,403 --> 02:04:47,487
it always makes me laugh.

1701
02:04:48,906 --> 02:04:50,950
Andy Dufresne,

1702
02:04:51,034 --> 02:04:53,411
who crawled through a river of shit

1703
02:04:53,495 --> 02:04:55,580
and came out clean on the other side.

1704
02:04:56,790 --> 02:04:58,833
Andy Dufresne,

1705
02:04:58,917 --> 02:05:00,835
headed for the Pacific.

1706
02:05:03,422 --> 02:05:05,464
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1707
02:05:05,549 --> 02:05:09,760
And he says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1708
02:05:09,845 --> 02:05:13,014
Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1709
02:05:13,098 --> 02:05:15,349
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1710
02:05:15,434 --> 02:05:17,935
"These friends of mine
could use a couple of beers!"

1711
02:05:18,020 --> 02:05:20,104
- And he got it.
- And he got it!

1712
02:05:21,273 --> 02:05:23,649
Sometimes it makes me sad, though,

1713
02:05:23,734 --> 02:05:25,776
Andy being gone.

1714
02:05:25,861 --> 02:05:29,864
I have to remind myself
that some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1715
02:05:30,949 --> 02:05:33,034
Their feathers are just too bright.

1716
02:05:34,578 --> 02:05:36,621
And when they fly away,

1717
02:05:36,705 --> 02:05:40,625
the part of you that knows
it was a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1718
02:05:42,377 --> 02:05:43,836
But still...

1719
02:05:43,921 --> 02:05:48,091
the place you live in is that much more drab
and empty that they're gone.

1720
02:05:52,639 --> 02:05:54,890
I guess I just miss my friend.

1721
02:06:18,873 --> 02:06:20,749
Please sit down.

1722
02:06:26,339 --> 02:06:28,465
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1723
02:06:28,549 --> 02:06:31,927
Your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1724
02:06:32,011 --> 02:06:34,388
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1725
02:06:36,516 --> 02:06:38,600
Rehabilitated?

1726
02:06:40,144 --> 02:06:42,229
Well, now, let me see.

1727
02:06:43,273 --> 02:06:45,607
You know, I don't have any idea
what that means.

1728
02:06:47,403 --> 02:06:49,946
Well, it means you're ready to rejoin society...

1729
02:06:50,030 --> 02:06:52,573
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1730
02:06:54,952 --> 02:06:57,036
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1731
02:06:58,080 --> 02:07:00,331
A politician's word so that...

1732
02:07:00,416 --> 02:07:05,920
young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie and have a job.

1733
02:07:08,340 --> 02:07:10,425
What do you really want to know?

1734
02:07:11,593 --> 02:07:13,511
Am I sorry for what I did?

1735
02:07:13,595 --> 02:07:15,305
Well, are you?

1736
02:07:16,932 --> 02:07:19,517
There's not a day goes by I don't feel regret.

1737
02:07:21,103 --> 02:07:24,230
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1738
02:07:28,027 --> 02:07:30,111
I look back on the way I was then.

1739
02:07:32,698 --> 02:07:34,741
A young...

1740
02:07:34,825 --> 02:07:37,910
stupid kid who committed that terrible crime.

1741
02:07:41,749 --> 02:07:43,833
I wanna talk to him.

1742
02:07:45,211 --> 02:07:47,379
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1743
02:07:48,423 --> 02:07:50,507
tell him the way things are.

1744
02:07:52,677 --> 02:07:54,762
But I can't.

1745
02:07:55,972 --> 02:07:58,057
That kid's long gone.

1746
02:07:59,351 --> 02:08:01,435
This old man is all that's left.

1747
02:08:03,563 --> 02:08:05,064
I gotta live with that.

1748
02:08:06,399 --> 02:08:08,192
Rehabilitated?

1749
02:08:08,276 --> 02:08:10,277
It's just a bullshit word.

1750
02:08:10,362 --> 02:08:16,283
So you go on and stamp your form, sonny,
and stop wasting my time.

1751
02:08:17,369 --> 02:08:19,411
Because to tell you the truth,

1752
02:08:19,496 --> 02:08:21,997
I don't give a shit.

1753
02:09:48,211 --> 02:09:50,296
Here you go, miss.

1754
02:09:52,299 --> 02:09:53,757
Rest room break, boss?

1755
02:09:59,806 --> 02:10:04,101
You don't need to ask me every time you need
to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1756
02:10:05,312 --> 02:10:06,979
Yes, sir.

1757
02:10:17,032 --> 02:10:20,075
40 years
I've been asking permission to piss.

1758
02:10:21,077 --> 02:10:23,287
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1759
02:10:27,417 --> 02:10:29,502
There's a harsh truth to face.

1760
02:10:31,463 --> 02:10:33,797
No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.

1761
02:10:42,016 --> 02:10:45,477
All I do any more
is think of ways to break my parole...

1762
02:10:46,521 --> 02:10:48,605
..so maybe they'd send me back.

1763
02:10:54,111 --> 02:10:56,196
A terrible thing to live in fear.

1764
02:10:57,573 --> 02:11:00,951
Brooks Hatlen knew it, knew it all too well.

1765
02:11:03,120 --> 02:11:05,914
All I want is to be back
where things make sense,

1766
02:11:06,958 --> 02:11:09,459
where I won't have to be afraid all the time.

1767
02:11:12,338 --> 02:11:14,422
Only one thing stops me.

1768
02:11:15,466 --> 02:11:17,551
A promise I made to Andy.

1769
02:11:38,282 --> 02:11:40,366
Here it is.

1770
02:11:50,168 --> 02:11:52,253
Much obliged, sir.

1771
02:15:31,060 --> 02:15:32,352
Dear Red,

1772
02:15:32,436 --> 02:15:34,896
if you're reading this, you've gotten out.

1773
02:15:34,980 --> 02:15:39,234
And if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a little further.

1774
02:15:39,318 --> 02:15:41,903
You remember the name of the town, don't you?

1775
02:15:44,198 --> 02:15:46,282
Zihuatanejo.

1776
02:15:47,326 --> 02:15:48,535
I could use a good man

1777
02:15:48,619 --> 02:15:50,662
to help me get my project on wheels.

1778
02:15:50,746 --> 02:15:52,872
I'll keep an eye out for you

1779
02:15:52,957 --> 02:15:54,999
and the chessboard ready.

1780
02:15:56,043 --> 02:15:57,418
Remember, Red,

1781
02:15:57,503 --> 02:15:59,546
hope is a good thing.

1782
02:15:59,630 --> 02:16:01,673
Maybe the best of things.

1783
02:16:01,757 --> 02:16:03,842
And no good thing ever dies.

1784
02:16:04,885 --> 02:16:07,345
I will be hoping that this letter finds you

1785
02:16:07,429 --> 02:16:09,472
and finds you well.

1786
02:16:09,557 --> 02:16:12,058
Your friend, Andy.

1787
02:16:46,636 --> 02:16:50,514
Get busy living or get busy dying.

1788
02:16:53,018 --> 02:16:55,102
That's goddamn right.

1789
02:17:00,609 --> 02:17:02,735
For the second time in my life,

1790
02:17:02,819 --> 02:17:04,904
I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1791
02:17:06,573 --> 02:17:08,657
Parole violation.

1792
02:17:08,658 --> 02:17:12,369
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1793
02:17:13,622 --> 02:17:15,664
Not for an old crook like me.

1794
02:17:15,749 --> 02:17:17,833
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1795
02:17:21,546 --> 02:17:25,675
I find I'm so excited I can barely sit still
or hold a thought in my head.

1796
02:17:26,719 --> 02:17:29,721
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1797
02:17:29,805 --> 02:17:32,515
A free man at the start of a long journey

1798
02:17:32,600 --> 02:17:35,518
whose conclusion is uncertain.

1799
02:17:38,397 --> 02:17:40,565
I hope I can make it across the border.

1800
02:17:42,443 --> 02:17:45,236
I hope to see my friend and shake his hand.

1801
02:17:47,615 --> 02:17:50,825
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1802
02:17:53,579 --> 02:17:55,455
I hope.

